{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489273"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:11:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"623"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/623"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.57,0.34,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78154"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"486"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78154"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of dark red urine. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He reports three similar episodes over the past two years, with the most recent occurring six months ago and resolving spontaneously. He has had coryzal symptoms including sore throat and non-productive cough for three days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 160/105 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Urinalysis reveals blood 3+ and protein 1+.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Henoch-Schonlein purpura","IgA nephropathy","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","Goodpasture syndrome","Alport syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common form of glomerulonephritis worldwide. The key diagnostic features are recurrent episodes of visible haematuria that typically occur during or immediately following an upper respiratory tract infection, often called synpharyngitic haematuria. The patient\u0027s age, gender, and pattern of presentation are highly characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Schonlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is also mediated by IgA but typically presents with additional features including palpable purpura, arthralgia, and abdominal pain. The absence of these extra-renal manifestations makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs 1-3 weeks after a streptococcal infection, not during the acute infection. It is more common in children and usually presents as a single episode rather than recurrent episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoodpasture syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies and typically presents with concurrent pulmonary haemorrhage (manifesting as haemoptysis) and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis. The absence of pulmonary symptoms and the recurrent nature of symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlport syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited condition affecting type IV collagen. While it can cause haematuria, it typically presents in childhood and is associated with sensorineural hearing loss and ocular abnormalities. The late onset and absence of these associated features make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IgA nephropathy classically presents with episodes of visible haematuria during or immediately after upper respiratory tract infections.","Recurrent episodes of visible haematuria with concurrent infections suggest IgA nephropathy rather than other forms of glomerulonephritis.","Hypertension is a common finding in IgA nephropathy and may indicate chronic kidney damage."],"references":["Lai, K., Tang, S., Schena, F. et al. IgA nephropathy. Nat Rev Dis Primers 2, 16001 (2016). Available at: https://doi.org/10.1038/nrdp.2016.1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"623"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:50:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:50:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"623"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78154"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t